text:
Full description from birds of the world:

 Male 16 cm (31 cm inclusive of central rectrices), 43‚Äì65 g; female 19 cm, 38‚Äì58 g. Very small paradisaeid with upper ridge of culmen sharply keeled to knife edge (as in
and
). Male nominate race has crimson

, chin, breast and upperparts, more orange on forecrown and tuft of elongate plush feathering over culmen base, discrete spot of black feathering above central eye showing iridescent dark green; elongate mantle "cape" ¬≠feathers, back, rump, tertials and some upper¬≠wing-coverts crimson to carmine with intense white iridescence, uppertail-coverts duller, more orange (less glossy crimson); upperwing predominantly glossy crimson, flight-feathers and some coverts variably brown; uppertail dark brownish-olive with brown-orange outer feather edges, elongated central feather pair reduced to fine bare red-brown central shafts with remarkable terminal spiral discs, latter (formed of inner feather web) iridescent metallic dark green with bronzed-yellow sheen; lowermost crimson throat feathers finely tipped pale buff where they meet narrow breast shield of iridescent dark green (can appear jet-black to burnished green-yellow in some lights); on each side of shield several elongate erectile fan-shaped olive-brown pectoral plumes, these pinkish-buff immediately prior to a broad iridescent tip of metallic bright green; remaining
white; iris pale brown to dark brown or greyish-brown; bill ivory-yellow, mouth pale aqua-green; legs violaceous cobalt-blue to blue-grey.

is similar in size to male, but tail (excluding central rectrices) longer; plumage radically different, in cryptically drab-coloured olive-brown above, with rusty margins on greater coverts, remiges and tail feathers, often with paler, buffier area above eye, variably buff on breast, flanks and lower belly, and entire underside finely and uniformly barred dark brown; bill and legs duller than adult male's. Newly fledged juvenile (11 days) has upper head brown, tinged russet, with light superciliary stripe with dark spot above, upperparts and tail grey-brown, wing feathers darker brown, greater coverts and outer primaries red-brown, chin grey-tinged brownish-yellow with fine streaks and points, underparts light grey with dark barring, iris grey-brown, bill-horn coloured, legs paler blue than female; immature male like adult, younger (darker-billed) individuals having much orange-rufous on wing-coverts and outer edges of flight-feathers, and orange-rufous wash on upper breast and (more so) to side of it, but steadily losing this as acquiring increasingly paler bill and then the red of adult plumage, rectrices pointed at tips; subadult male variable, like adult female with few feathers of adult male plumage intruding to like adult male with few feathers of female-like plumage remaining; with age, male acquires progressively shorter outer rectrices while simultaneously gaining progressively longer central pair. Race
is very like nominate, differs only in having central pair of rectrices and bill slightly longer.

messages.text:
Bird photography is so much easier:

1. Look for bird until found, if cannot find just go home
2. If bird found is rare, take record shots (simply aim + press button), if bird fly away before this happens just break down and cry; occasionally swear at the lousy ass autofocus
3. Look for a better angle, 90% of the time it‚Äôs to get rid of backlight
4. Take photos until bird fly away, until bored, or until someone boots you out of your spot
5. Repeat from step 3
6. Go home
7. Realises setting is wrong and everything turns out crappy
8. Questions the meaning of life, resolve by going to sleep
9. Repeat

messages.text:
I don't consider this book very technical -- I am sure his clinical writings are far more technical.

I think its more his style and way of thought that makes his works difficult to digest -- convoluted, abstract, and lacking sufficient concrete examples. Because of the nature of the subject, a lot of interpretation is also needed, and that makes it even more challenging.

messages.text:
I tried to read his "Archetypes and the Collective Unconscious" and decided to stop halfway üòÇ

This one is even more abstract because it deals with a fundementally intangible and unobservable (at least not directly) topic -- the unconsciousness. There's a lot of symbolism, and dreams in this text. Fascinating because a lot of symbols and patterns recur all around us, but very little application unless one's a Jung practitioner.

and on my way home I was thinking about it ‚Äì and it seems like when people talk a lot, but you don't see actions, they talk a lot bout themselves, their words are always matched by an agenda etc. 

in short, the lack of positivity and honesty + having hidden agendas in conversation was very exhausting ü•≤

Because those who are actually able to would not have said issues in the first place -- this
to be the reason why the success rate of abuse conselling is so abysmally low, because those that can be helped are already predisposed to not have the problem in the first place!

messages.text:
It can be summarised as follows:
1. Male catch fish.
2. Male attempts to passe fish to female. Can fail.
3. Female consumes fish, after which she might (a) simply fly away, (b) stay put but reject the male‚Äôs advances (high chance) which prompts further feeding efforts, or (c) allows the male to mount.
4. Male mounts, after which he is either successful or nothing happens (and nobody knows why).
5. Repeat from step 1.

text:
In fact just this part is even more generalised, and useful in just about every situation when one party wants to control the other:

You are believing that your precious feelings should rule over the choices other people make. You are saying that your precious feelings are more important than the agency or happiness of other people. That‚Äôs disrespectful. And controlling.

Another hard lesson to learn:
They have just as much right to choose how to live as you do. They are not supporting actors in the story of You, You, You. They do not exist just to make you feel good.

messages.text:
And technically ‚Äúcontrol‚Äù is fine and dandy since one cannot ‚Äútrust‚Äù something non-sentient; problem arises when one has to deal with another sentient being.

So it appears that trust or to control another being are two very common but completely opposite approaches one could take to deal with fears and insecurities. 

The former is developmental in nature in that it attempts to addresses one‚Äôs own problems; the latter externalizes the problems via projection, and doesn‚Äôt actually fix things internally.

we had our sketch books prepped, but cause it was the first sem/ first week of school (of uni) so no tutorials, the entire class went to the library to wait for the next lesson, which is about 3 hours away 

I'd nothing to do so I just whipped out my sketchbook and started exploring some work, it wasn't uncommon practice for us back in poly to do so, and it has become habitual to always carry one 

I just so happen to have my old pen brush, and it caught the eye of a girl in my class, and she asked "what's that" and "where can I get that"

so I just shared lor and let her try, and she just went "Chey I thought what, it's the pen that is great, not the artist penning this book" 

I just sat there feeling like a fool like ... what sister I don't even know your name so I just left the area in the pretense of a book search 

and I heard her say "eh finish her ink la"

messages.text:
As an aside, I believe that you are in a position to pursue pretty much whatever, being neither advantaged nor disadvantaged in either, and reasonably intelligent overall.

Because you are neither a dominant thinker or feeler, you are first and foremost a perceiver ‚Äî an irrational being whose priority is information gathering and/or generating. 

Rational judgment and decision-making only come after, and these have the tendency to be seen as ‚Äúleft‚Äù or ‚Äúright‚Äù brained.

Because you are neither a dominant thinker or feeler, you are first and foremost a perceiver ‚Äî an irrational being whose priority is information gathering and/or generating. 

Rational judgment and decision-making only come after, and these have the tendency to be seen as ‚Äúleft‚Äù or ‚Äúright‚Äù brained.

ùìüùì™ùì∑ùìΩùì≤ ùìëùì≤ùìªùì≠ ùì°ùì™ùì¨ùìÆ - ùìôùì∏ùì±ùì∏ùìª 2024
Dates:  27 & 28 April 2024
Rules & Regulations
Below are the rules and regulations under which the Bird Race team members are expected to adhere to.  All participants must familiarize themselves with the under-mentioned rules and agree and comply with them fully to compete. Failure to do so will lead to team penalties or disqualification.
Date:  27 & 28 April 2024
Start:  Flag off from Panti Bird Sanctuary Complex at 10.00am on 27/4/2024
End:  Official Log Sheet to be handed in by 11.00am on 28/4/2024
Location:  Participants are allowed to bird within Panti Bird Sanctuary and on foot only. 
Categories & Team composition:
1)      Novice Team*:  3 pax per team 
2)      Advanced Team:  3 pax per team
3)      Photo Race Team:  2 pax per team
*Novice Team: Team members with 2 years or less of birding experience.  The organisers may, at their discretion, upgrade participants from Novice to Advance.
Counting Species:
            a. All teams will be issued the official bird race Log Sheet.
            b. For the Novice and Advance categories, species must be sighted by majority of the team (i.e. at least 2 of the team members) and their identity agreed by all members of the team before it can be registered. Species identified by calls only must not be included.
            c. For the Photo Race Category, all species listed must be photographed and correctly identified before it can be registered.
            d. Species registered by all categories must be submitted in the official bird race Log Sheet.
            e. Teams can use draft lists during the race but must hand in the official completed list to the arbitrators at the finish line by the stipulated time. (NOTE: Teams are advised to allocate sufficient time for checking and finalizing before the finish time.  Photo Race Teams must allocate extra time to sort and save images into the Pen-drive).
            f. The arbitrators may elect to penalize a team for late submission (one species for each minute).
            g. Handwriting in submissions list must be legible.  The arbitrators reserve the right to delete any species because of illegible handwriting.
            h. All team members must race together as a team during the duration of race.
 
Photo Race Category
a. Participants must submit the following at the end of the race:
i. Completed official bird race Log Sheet.
ii. ONE pen-drive with the images (JPEG) captured during the race.
b. Participants need to bring their own laptop and pen-drive to sort out the pictures before submission (pen-drive will be returned to participants after judging).
c. All species photographed by the team shall be consolidated into only pen-drive before submission.
d. Only Pen-drive to be used for submission.
e. Only ONE picture per species shall be submitted.
f. Species photographed must be correctly identified and recorded into official log sheet.
g. Pictures must be submitted in JPEG format.  Please ensure original exif data must be present for all photographs.
h. The arbitrators reserve the right to delete any species which cannot be positively identified e.g. some juvenile birds or pond-herons in non-breeding plumage.
i. Note:  A Photo Race is NOT a photography competition.  It‚Äôs the same as any bird race but each species must be photographed and a photo of the species submitted together with the log sheet as mentioned above.
 
Results of the Race
a. The winning team in each category will be the one with the highest total number of species recorded, and accepted by the judges.
b. In the event of a tie, the team who submitted the Log Sheet earlier will be the winner.
c. The arbitrators‚Äô decision will be final, and no appeals will be entertained.
 
Submission of records for rare or unusual sightings

sudden memory unlocked: I remember that night when we were on our way to panti (this was Nov then) and she was having a convo with Dennis and myself in the car ‚Äì having big dilemma whether to leave her current posting, accept a job offer, or take a leave/break

and before this topic came about, I was just saying oh I just told my mum I'm heading out but not Panti specifically. and her reply was "maybe you 30 alr they don't care about you"

fast forward after the job conversation, she said "my dad will not accept the reason of taking a break for a job...maybe I need to wait till 30 so that they won't care about me" 

at that moment it felt so weird to hear that then haha felt like there was something more to what was said

messages.text:
I think in general one should simply approach without any hidden agenda ‚Äî do any such hidden motives even work in the long run anyways? 

A purely platonic friendship can evolve healthily to a romantic relationship if it was a natural progression and not part of a hidden agenda in the first place. In this situation even if the romantic relationship fails the underlying friendship can still be (but not necessarily always) preserved.

My wife thinks that a romantic relationship is basically physical intimacy built on a solid bedrock of friendship, and I tend to agree.
